{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2607"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2607"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.26,0.1,0.17,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44613"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2607"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29487"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48634"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44613"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old woman from a high-level of care nursing home is admitted to hospital with a five day history of diarrhoea and abdominal pain. She has a medical history of reflux and peripheral vascular disease. Her medications include pantoprazole and aspirin. No similar symptoms have been reported by other nursing home residents. On examination her pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, and temperature 37.9\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her abdomen is soft to palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe receives initial fluid resuscitation and ongoing maintenance fluid. On day two her stool sample shows non-typhoid Salmonella and she is started on ciprofloxacin 500 mg BD. On day three, she deteriorates with worsening fevers and abdominal pain. Blood cultures confirm Salmonella bacteraemia. She has generalised abdominal tenderness and there is concern about a potential complication from the Salmonella bacteraemia. Further investigations are considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT angiography","Lumbar puncture","CT brain","Chest X-ray","Urogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-typhoidal Salmonella bacteraemia may occur as a result of intestinal Salmonella infection. A number of host factors predispose to Salmonella bacteraemia including extremes of age, immunosuppression, chronic liver disease and haemoglobinopathies, as well alteration of the gastrointestinal tract by use of antibiotics, malnutrition or acid suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESalmonella bacteraemia may result in a number of complications affecting a wide variety of sites including the urinary tract, lungs, pleura, heart as well as bones and joints. An uncommon but important complication of salmonella bacteraemia is endovascular infection leading to a mycotic (or infected) aneurysm. Endovascular infections have been noted to occur in 10-20 % of patients \u0026gt; 50 years old with Salmonella bacteraemia. The classic presentation of an infected aneurysm is a painful, pulsatile, and enlarging mass with systemic features of infection. Salmonella typically targets the aorta, particularly if already diseased with atherosclerosis. This patient is complaining of abdominal pain and there is abdominal tenderness. It would be quite reasonable to put her present condition down to end-vascular infection. The best diagnostic investigation for a suspected mycotic aneurysm is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E (MR angiography is an alternative if intravenous contrast is contraindicated).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be a useful investigation if urinary tract colonisation was suspected. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed if there were respiratory symptom. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful if meningoencephalitis was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aortitis is a rare but important complication of Salmonella bacteraemia"],"references":["Darby J, Sheorey H. Searching for Salmonella. Aust Fam Physician. 2008;37(10):806-10. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/8860f29c-bb86-499f-a16a-bd748cd6cf59/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29487"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2607"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29487"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-24T16:16:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-14T17:45:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2607"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"hea